Photo dump of Suomi 🇫🇮
•
I have so much love for this country. It was my second time making my way to Finland & when asked why I like it so much, I always answer the same thing. It’s unremarkable. But wait… why would I love something unremarkable? So many places boast incredible reasons to visit, yet are plagued by many cons that make the experience less than stellar (ie: Paris has world renowned landmarks, and beautiful architecture. But the city is overcrowded, people are notoriously rude & it’s a little dirty). But then you have Helsinki (and Finland as a whole). The architecture is tasteful but unpretentious. The food is fresh, wholesome but humble. The weather may be cold to most, but for a Canadian it’s actually incredibly mild. The people are a little reserved but once warmed up, incredibly generous & friendly. The city has life and is big enough to entertain, but small enough to not feel crowded. The culture has its quirks & uniqueness (saunas… everywhere, liquorice, thinking Santa is Finnish & not Canadian etc). People love their country & there’s a sense of patriotism towards it (second only to the USA). It’s modern yet traditional. Developed yet connected to nature. Everything just works. And this is why unremarkable is beautiful. Nothing stands out. And that’s exactly what, makes it stand out. It doesn’t try to be anything else, than itself.

#2022 recap here we go. So much love for everyone who was part of it and who lived it side by side. You are all the damn best 🙏🏼
•
Started the year with a list of 25 things to do, and I hit most of them (except be a ninja in bed aka stay 24h in a row in bed). I’ll start out 2023 doing the same thing and I encourage everyone to list 25 big or small things they want to do this year. And when you’re done, please share it with me, I’d love to see what y’all are going to get up to. 
•
This year, I gallivanted quite a bit. Here’s a summary of the places I’ve been. Finland🇫🇮, France🇫🇷, Sweden🇸🇪, Estonia🇪🇪, Italy🇮🇹, Hungary🇭🇺, Netherlands🇳🇱, Germany🇩🇪, Mexico🇲🇽, Houston🇺🇸, Florida🇺🇸. And it ain’t done, flying to Alaska in 2days for a last second mileage run 🤘🏼

2023 under the palm trees again! This is the new tradition and I won’t accept anything less 🌴
•
This year is all about doing the opposite of normal. Breaking out of the matrix. Going against the grain. Finding your deep purpose. Taking that risk. Being weird. Normal is boring (and I find society mediocre anyway). Cheers y’all🍾🎉

“Normality is a paved road: it’s comfortable to walk, but no flowers grow on it” - Van Gogh
•
Like clockwork, fall comes around and the gallivanting begins. This time across France for a bit. I recently took the first (of hopefully many) sommelier course. So how fitting to put that new found knowledge to the test in one of the richest wine region of the world. I still can’t identify any aromas through smell nor tell what tannins feel like but I sure know how to drink it 😜
•
Pictured here: a little breathtaking moment on a gloomy day on the side of an Irish road, near the western tip of the country, near Dunmore Head. I meant to post this, along many others from Florida, Iceland, Chile and even home in Montreal but this summer has been a whirlwind and I took some distance from all socials in order to regain perspective. And I did :)

The altiplano - A diary pt.1
Read below 👇🏻
•
1- The path to El Tatio. In the heart of the Altiplano, lies the 3rd biggest geyser field in the world. Getting there is treacherous but takes you through jaw dropping terrain at altitudes topping out 15,000feet/4500meters. 
•
2- One of many Martian looking salt flats at the junction between Chile, Bolivia and Argentina. This one, has a phallic twist ;)
•
3- The crew. In the most unlikely place, I met a couple Americans from Boston who were adventuring across the Altiplano. We formed a crew and explored some uncharted spots together (and ventured to Argentina. See below) . Sidenote: not the place you want a flat tire. 
•
4- Can you spot the intruder? 
•
5- Isolated. If you’ve ever wanted to feel completely disconnected from your daily life, this is the place to go. Not a soul (other than Vicuñas) for miles around. 
•
6- 15,000 feet of elevation is NO jokes. At that altitude the air pressure is roughly half that of sea level. AMS hits you like a freight train. In some cases it leads to Pulmonary or Cerebral Edema which can kill big time. Pictured here, my SpO2. Normal is 95-100%. Under 90% is trouble…
•
7- Vicuñas. The cutest cousin of the Alpaca. 
•
8- Ruta 27, one of the world’s highest road, takes you from Chile to Argentina through the Andes mountain range. (Ps. This is your sign to join your local rotary club 😂)
•
9- Paso de Jama, the crossing between Chile and Argentina is located about 20kms inside Argentina. Not pictured: us getting denied entry into Argentina and turned the fk back around… 
•
10- silly goose time on rocky protrusions 🙃

The Atacama desert - A diary pt.2
Read below 👇🏻
•
1- Valle de la Luna. At sunset, this outer-worldly landscape gives rise to one of the nicest sunsets I’ve ever seen (it rivals siesta key). Being in a desert means that you can physically feel a drastic shift in temperature as the sun sets. From hot to freezing cold, in the span on minutes. 
•
2- Same same, but different 😜
•
3- Volcán Licancabur. This volcano smack on the border between Bolivia and Chile has at its peak a crater containing Licancabur lake, one of the highest lakes in the world (~19,500feet). It’s also the point with the highest recorded UV index on the planet at 43.3 (for comparison, Montreal rarely gets over 9 in mid July). 
•
4- Ripping it through the Atacama desert off-road style had to be the most fun I’ve had in years. I used to say that the ultimate feeling of freedom was speeding >250km/h on a sports bike… but this topped it.
•
5- El Tatio. In the middle of the world’s 3rd most active geyser field, sits the squirting nipple. Or at least that’s what I named it. 
•
6- The Atacama desert is host to several space observatories. Due to its remote, arid and high altitude location, it is considered the best place on earth to watch the night sky. I headed to the middle of the desert one night with some blankets, pillows and a bottle of wine. I laid down, and gazed in awe at the Milky Way painted across the sky. Even counted a few shooting stars. In that very moment, peace found me. 
•
7- Vicuñas are cute, but I ate them. Lol
•
8- Not the Dead Sea, but floating just the same. This is a salazar aka salt flat in the middle of the desert. The salinity is so high that you float. What isn’t pictured here is how fking cold the water was. This rivalled jumping in the frozen Baltic Sea in January. 
•
9- One of the best hotel I’ve ever stayed at. A true oasis in the desert. I could have stayed for months (and did consider it). All of the world’s problems seemed to evaporate here.
•
10- Valle de la Luna again… because come on… Look at that!

So this year took an unexpected turn 🖤
•
Now admit it, who here had a clue about this? As much as I share a portion of my life extensively on here, there couldn’t be less of an accurate depiction of who I am than Instagram. It’s like an iceberg, 90% is underwater, out of sight and unknown. 
I’ve always kept my private life, incredibly guarded. And that’s not about to change.
•
However Jax wanted to come on and wish everyone a merry Christmas! 🎄
•
He’s the greatest gift I could have ever wished for this year. He’s the happiest lil kid and his smile is the most infectious thing in the world. And I credit it for allowing me to survive 2023, one of the most challenging year I’ve ever confronted.
•
He also reminds me of what’s truly important in life. It’s definitely not what modern society peddles, thats for sure. And  it’s given me a new purpose going forward. Things appear so different from this side of life. 
•
Oh and yes, you can now call me daddy 😉

#2023 recap here we go. So much love for everyone who crossed my path. The moments may have come to past, but the memories will live forever. 

➡️ Here’s a quick summary of the year : 

-Welcomed into the world my first son
-Bought a building 
-Survived altitude sickness at 15,000feet
-Visited 13 countries + a new continent & hemisphere
-Escaped another winter
-Reached year 9 with my company, BizBiz
-Took 40 flights totalling +150,000kms
-Spent 159 nights outside Canada 
-Dealt with 3 lawsuits 🙃

🌎And the places I’ve spent time in: 
Florida🇺🇸 (obviously), The Netherlands🇳🇱, Germany🇩🇪, Finland🇫🇮, Sweden🇸🇪, Ireland🇮🇪, Iceland🇮🇸, Chile🇨🇱, Argentina🇦🇷, France🇫🇷, Switzerland🇨🇭, Estonia🇪🇪, Canada🇨🇦 (sadly). 

Enjoy every single moment you have, because a bad day is coming for all of us sooner or later 🖤
